label.value: increased duration of mitotic DNA damage checkpoint during cellular response to UV during mitotic S phase

value.value: A cell cycle checkpoint phenotype in which the duration of cell cycle arrest or delay due to regulation by any mitotic DNA damage checkpoint is greater than in wild type during a cellular response to ultraviolet (UV) light, when cells are exposed to UV during S phase of the mitotic cell cycle.

label.value: decreased rate of cell separation after cytokinesis

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the rate, or speed, of cell separation after cytokinesis is decreased.

label.value: increased cellular HMW SUMO conjugate level

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of protein having high molecular mass due to polySUMO conjugation is greater than normal.

label.value: decreased cellular HMW SUMO conjugate level

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of protein having high molecular mass due to polySUMO conjugation is lower than normal.

label.value: decreased rate of protein degradation during vegetative growth

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the rate, or speed, of protein degradation is decreased.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: sister kinetochore dissociation in meiotic metaphase I, normal chromosome segregation in meiosis I, and sister chromatid non-disjunction in meiosis II

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype in which sister kinetochores separate during the first meiotic nuclear division, homologous chromosomes undergo normal reductional division, but sister chromatids divide unequally in meiosis II. Normally sister kinetochores remain together until meiosis II.  Normally sister kinetochores remain together until meiosis II.

definition.value: This term describes the premature separation of paired, intact sister kinetochores. It has a related synonym using "split kinetochores" because that phrase is often used in the literature to describe this phenotype. It should not be confused with the FYPO terms that have "split kinetochore" in the names, because those names refer to cases where a single kinetochore has broken into parts.

label.value: sister kinetochore dissociation in meiotic metaphase I with  equational sister chromatid  segregation in meiosis I

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which sister kinetochores become separated during the first meiotic nuclear division, and sister chromatids subsequently separate to result in equational segregation. Equational sister chromatid separation is caused by  bi-orientated attachment of sister chromatids.

definition.value: Sister kinetochores may separate in meiosis I due to problems with either sister chromatid cohesion or kinetochore attachment to microtubules. Therefore consider also annotating to 'abnormal attachment of spindle microtubules to kinetochore involved in homologous chromosome segregation' (FYPO:0000209), 'decreased meiotic sister chromatid cohesion' (FYPO:0002093), or 'merotelic kinetochore attachment during meiosis I' (FYPO:0005638). This term describes the premature separation of paired, intact sister kinetochores. It has a related synonym using "split kinetochores" because that phrase is often used in the literature to describe this phenotype. It should not be confused with the FYPO terms that have "split kinetochore" in the names, because those names refer to cases where a single kinetochore has broken into parts.

label.value: delayed onset of protein localization to spindle during meiosis I

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the localization of a protein to the spindle begins later than normal during the first meiotic nuclear division.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: delayed onset of protein localization from kinetochore to spindle during meiosis I

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the localization of a protein from kinetochores to the spindle begins later than normal during the first meiotic nuclear division.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: normal onset of metaphase/anaphase transition of meiosis I

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which the metaphase/anaphase transition of the first meiotic nuclear division begins at the normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) time relative to other cell cycle events.

label.value: merotelic kinetochore attachment during meiosis I

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which the attachment of spindle microtubules to the kinetochore during the first meiotic nuclear division results in the connection of a single kinetochore to both spindle poles.

label.value: normal RNA level during cellular response to iron ion starvation

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of RNA measured in a cell during a cellular response to iron ion starvation is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type). Total RNA or a specific RNA may be affected.

definition.value: We recommend noting which RNA(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: abnormal meiotic centromere clustering with centromeres dissociated from spindle pole body

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which centromere clustering is abnormal during one or both meiotic nuclear divisions, such that centromeres dissociate from the spindle pole body, but do not cluster with each other.

label.value: abnormal chromosome segregation during meiosis I with premature sister kinetochore separation, lagging chromosomes, and normal chromosome separation

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which kinetochores become separated during the first meiotic nuclear division, and in which homologous chromosomes do not move towards the spindle poles at the same time during anaphase, but are eventually separated normally.

definition.value: This term describes the premature separation of paired, intact sister kinetochores. It has a related synonym using "split kinetochores" because that phrase is often used in the literature to describe this phenotype. It should not be confused with the FYPO terms that have "split kinetochore" in the names, because those names refer to cases where a single kinetochore has broken into parts.

label.value: abnormal meiotic homologous chromosome biorientation with abnormal kinetochore orientation

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which homologous chromosome biorientation is abnormal during meiosis, with chromosomes that are not correctly oriented with the kinetochores facing outwards. Homologous chromosome biorientation is the process in which the sister centromeres of one chromosome attach to microtubules that emanate from the same spindle pole, ensuring that homologous maternal and paternal chromosomes are pulled in opposite directions at anaphase of meiosis I.

label.value: decreased protein localization to cell tip, with protein mislocalized to nucleus and spindle pole body

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to the cell tip is decreased, and an increased amount of the protein is instead detected in the nucleus and at the spindle pole body.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: normal protein localization to nucleus during cellular response to hydroxyurea

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to the nucleus is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) during a cellular response to hydroxyurea.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: resistance to Cutin-1

value.value: An increased chemical resistance phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cells grow in the presence of a higher concentration of Cutin-1 (N-carbamoyl-2-(triphenyl-lambda-5-phosphanylidene)acetamide) than normal.

definition.value: Cutin-1 has CAS registry number 53296-08-5.

label.value: abnormal kinetochore morphology

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype in which the size, shape, or structure of the kinetochore is abnormal.

definition.value: Note that an abnormal kinetochore organization process may, but does not necessarily, result in abnormal kinetochore structure.

label.value: split kinetochore

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype in which the kinetochore is divided into two or more parts.

label.value: sister kinetochore dissociation in meiotic metaphase I

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype in which sister kinetochores separate during the first meiotic nuclear division. Normally sister kinetochores remain together until meiosis II.

definition.value: This term describes the premature separation of paired, intact sister kinetochores. It has a related synonym using "split kinetochores" because that phrase is often used in the literature to describe this phenotype. It should not be confused with the FYPO terms that have "split kinetochore" in the names, because those names refer to cases where a single kinetochore has broken into parts.

label.value: increased duration of protein localization to telomere

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the duration of localization of a protein to the telomere of a chromosome is longer than normal.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: normal onset of premeiotic DNA replication

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which premeiotic DNA replication begins at the normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) time relative to other cell cycle events.

label.value: abnormal nuclear morphology during meiosis I

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype in which the size, shape, or structure of the nucleus is abnormal during the first meiotic nuclear division.

definition.value: Note that an abnormal nucleus organization process may, but does not necessarily, result in abnormal nuclear morphology.

label.value: abnormal spindle morphology during meiosis I

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype in which the size, shape, or structure of the spindle is abnormal during the first meiotic nuclear division.

definition.value: Note that an abnormal spindle organization process may, but does not necessarily, result in abnormal spindle morphology.

label.value: increased level of iron ion starvation-induced proteins during glutathione starvation

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of protein encoded by genes normally induced during iron ion starvation measured in a cell is higher than normal when the cell is subject to glutathione starvation.

label.value: decreased level of iron assimilation gene mRNA during vegetative growth

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of one or more iron assimilation RNAs measured in a cell is lower than normal (i.e. lower than observed in wild-type cells). Iron assimilation RNAs are transcribed from genes whose products are involved in any process in which iron is solubilized and transported into a cell.

definition.value: Consider annotating to a term describing abnormal transcription or abnormal regulation of transcription, but note that changes in RNA levels may result from changes in RNA stability as well as changes in transcription.

label.value: normal level of iron assimilation gene mRNA during vegetative growth

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of one or more iron assimilation RNAs measured in a cell is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type). Iron assimilation RNAs are transcribed from genes whose products are involved in any process in which iron is solubilized and transported into a cell.

definition.value: Consider annotating to a term describing abnormal transcription or abnormal regulation of transcription, but note that changes in RNA levels may result from changes in RNA stability as well as changes in transcription.

label.value: abolished iron ion binding

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which iron ion binding by a gene product does not occur. The affected gene product may be encoded by the mutated gene, or by a different gene.

label.value: normal frequency of meiotic crossover associated with gene conversion

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which the frequency of crossover associated with a gene conversion event during meiotic recombination is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

label.value: abnormal frequency of meiotic crossover associated with gene conversion

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which the frequency of crossover associated with a gene conversion event during meiotic recombination is abnormal.

label.value: increased frequency of meiotic crossover associated with gene conversion

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which the frequency of crossover associated with a gene conversion event during meiotic recombination is increased.

definition.value: This phenotype potentially reflects a change in the crossover/non-crossover decision pathway.

label.value: decreased frequency of meiotic crossover associated with gene conversion

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which the frequency of crossover associated with a gene conversion event during meiotic recombination is decreased.

definition.value: This phenotype potentially reflects a change in the crossover/non-crossover decision pathway.

label.value: increased transcription during nitrogen starvation

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which transcription occurs to a greater extent than normal when the cell is subject to nitrogen starvation. All genes, or a specific subset of genes, may be affected.

definition.value: Use this term if there is evidence, such as labeled nucleotide incorporation, showing that transcription rather than RNA stability is affected; otherwise, use 'decreased RNA level' (FYPO:0000826).

label.value: increased transcription from TR box

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which transcription from a promoter that contains one or more TR boxes occurs to a greater extent than normal.

label.value: abnormal re-entry into mitotic cell cycle after arrest in response to heat shock

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which re-entry into the mitotic cell cycle is abnormal after arrest resulting from heat shock.

label.value: viable elongated cell during nitrogen starvation

value.value: A cell morphology phenotype in which a cell is viable, and becomes elongated, i.e. has a greater length and length:diameter ratio than normal, when the cell is subject to nitrogen starvation.

definition.value: Note that wild-type cells become shorter under nitrogen starvation conditions than under nitrogen-replete conditions, and that mutant cells subjected to nitrogen starvation may have lengths similar to wild type cells under non-starved conditions. Also note that this term is classified as a type of abnormal cell shape, because under a given set of conditions wild-type cells are never seen with the proportions (length:diameter ratio) observed in elongated cells. Small cells, in contrast, have the same proportions as a subset of wild-type cells, and simply do not grow to the full length seen in wild type. This term can be used for any circumstances in which cells are starved for nitrogen. Note that cells may enter G0 (quiescence) when subjected to prolonged nitrogen starvation; this term is not restricted to G0.

label.value: abnormal actin cytoskeleton

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype in which the amount, distribution, or morphology of all or part of the actin cytoskeleton is abnormal.

definition.value: Note that an abnormal actin cytoskeleton organization process may, but does not necessarily, result in a physically abnormal actin cytoskeleton.

label.value: abnormal actin cytoskeleton during meiosis

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype in which the amount, distribution, or morphology of all or part of the actin cytoskeleton is abnormal during one or both meiotic nuclear divisions.

definition.value: Note that an abnormal actin cytoskeleton organization process may, but does not necessarily, result in a physically abnormal actin cytoskeleton.

label.value: premature protein localization to nucleus during vegetative growth

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to the nucleus begins earlier than normal.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: sensitive to cAMP

value.value: A phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cells show increased sensitivity to cyclic AMP (cAMP). Cells stop growing (and may die) at a concentration of cAMP that allows wild type cells to grow.

label.value: increased septation index during cellular response to methyl methanesulfonate

value.value: A cell population phenotype in which the septation index is higher than normal in a population that is exposed to methyl methanesulfonate. The septation index is the proportion of the population undergoing septation at any given time.

label.value: decreased protein localization to nucleus during mitosis

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to the nucleus is decreased during mitosis.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: decreased level of ubiquitinated protein in cell during cellular response to methyl methanesulfonate

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of ubiquitinated protein measured the cell is lower than normal during a cellular response to methyl methanesulfonate. Total protein or a specific protein may be affected.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: increased level of ubiquitinated protein in cell during cellular response to methyl methanesulfonate

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of ubiquitinated protein measured the cell is higher than normal during a cellular response to methyl methanesulfonate. Total protein or a specific protein may be affected.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: normal protein deubiquitination following cellular response to methyl methanesulfonate during vegetative growth

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the deubiquitination of one or more specific proteins, or of specific protein sites, is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) after cells have been exposed to methyl methanesulfonate.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: abolished protein deubiquitination following cellular response to methyl methanesulfonate during vegetative growth

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the deubiquitination of one or more specific proteins, or of specific protein sites, does not occur after cells have been exposed to methyl methanesulfonate.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: decreased number of Rad52 foci during mitotic S phase

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the number of sites at which the protein Rad52 (also called Rad22) accumulates is lower than normal during S phase of the mitotic cell cycle.

label.value: ubiquitinated protein absent from cell during vegetative growth

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of ubiquitinated protein measured in a cell is too low to detect. Total protein or a specific protein may be affected.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: decreased protein deubiquitination following cellular response to hydroxyurea during vegetative growth

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the deubiquitination of one or more specific proteins, or of specific protein sites, occurs to a lower extent than normal after cells have been exposed to hydroxyurea.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.
